<div id="review_4079402012" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4079402012" />
    <a title="Cheri" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/106692-cheri"><img alt="Cheri" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1639758828p2/106692.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4079402012?book_show_action=true">Jun 26, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cheri" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cheri" href="/user/show/106692-cheri">Cheri</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/11054030-daddy-long-legs">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/106692-cheri?shelf=coming-of-age">coming-of-age</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/106692-cheri?shelf=1910s">1910s</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/106692-cheri?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/106692-cheri?shelf=audible">audible</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/106692-cheri?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/106692-cheri?shelf=2021">2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4079402012" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10319784325205684817">3.5 Stars<br/><br/>When I was really young the only television set we had was an old B&amp;W set that was in our basement, and generally speaking, the only shows on it were typically really old movies. My older brother used to love watching old movies like Dracula, Godzilla or King Kong, but my favourites were always the ones with actors like Fred Astaire, or Jimmy Stewart. So when I was perusing some audible books this morning, I ran across this title and wondered if it was the book that the movie with Fred </span>
  <span id="freeText10319784325205684817" style="display:none">3.5 Stars<br /><br />When I was really young the only television set we had was an old B&amp;W set that was in our basement, and generally speaking, the only shows on it were typically really old movies. My older brother used to love watching old movies like Dracula, Godzilla or King Kong, but my favourites were always the ones with actors like Fred Astaire, or Jimmy Stewart. So when I was perusing some audible books this morning, I ran across this title and wondered if it was the book that the movie with Fred Astaire was based on. It’s been quite a while since I’ve seen it, and I had never even known it was based on a book, so I spent this morning reading the book while listening to this story narrated by Julia Whelan. <br />Written in 1912, this is far from being a ‘current’ theme, but all I remember from the movie was the dancing - it’s been a while, so I was happy to revisit this for the story. The young female narrator who has no family, Jerusha Abbott, has been taken under the wing of an anonymous gentleman, one of the Trustees. He will be her benefactor and responsible for her, her college fees, although he chooses to remain unknown to her. He has chosen her after reading one of her papers, and is planning for her to become a writer. She will also receive a ‘liberal’ allowance while attending college.<br /><br />The story beyond this point is mostly shared in the letters she writes to him, sent to one of his assistants. He does not write her back, but she writes to him frequently, her first letter written upon her arrival at her college, is addressed to <i>Dear Kind-Trustee-Who-Sends-Orphans-to-College,</i> and her letters have a young-girl chattiness that lends some authenticity to the time and her age, but at the same time it has a unique charm to it from the start. Eventually, rather than continue the lengthy way she addresses him in her first letter, she changes it to Daddy-Long-Legs, having only seen him as he walked away, it is the only thing she knows about him. <br /><br />Through her letters we learn about her life at college, her frustrations, her pleas to him to write back to her, the stories she’s writing, and the day in and day out of her life. While there isn’t much in the way of ‘thrilling’ or even outstanding moments until the end, there’s a unique charm to this that I enjoyed. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10319784325205684817" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


