<span id="freeTextContainer8641279043747428180">I always have a difficult time rating YA books. Do I rate them as I enjoy them <i>now</i>, or as I <i>would</i> have enjoyed them had I read it as a young adult? It&apos;s tricky.<br/><br/>As a young adult I would probably rate this as a five star read. As a forty something adult, I enjoyed it, but I wasn&apos;t like <i>all over it</i>. I&apos;d say 3.5 Stars. The author kept me reading, and I thought it was very sweet but I probably wouldn&apos;t reach for it to re-read anytime soon. And I&apos;m not sooo invested in the characters that I have to ru</span>
  <span id="freeText8641279043747428180" style="display:none">I always have a difficult time rating YA books. Do I rate them as I enjoy them <i>now</i>, or as I <i>would</i> have enjoyed them had I read it as a young adult? It's tricky.<br /><br />As a young adult I would probably rate this as a five star read. As a forty something adult, I enjoyed it, but I wasn't like <i>all over it</i>. I'd say 3.5 Stars. The author kept me reading, and I thought it was very sweet but I probably wouldn't reach for it to re-read anytime soon. And I'm not sooo invested in the characters that I have to run out and buy the sequel ASAP, though I will probably read it at some point.<br /><br />I won't give a synopsis because it's been done many times here on GR and I don't want to spoil things, but it really is a very cute story. You should read it.<br /><br /><b> February group read with the <i> dead writers society</i></b></span>
  <a data-text-id="8641279043747428180" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
