<div id="review_120222419" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/120222419" />
    <a title="Amy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2329228-amy"><img alt="Amy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1433629372p2/2329228.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/120222419?book_show_action=true">Sep 05, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amy" href="/user/show/2329228-amy">Amy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780140374551" href="/book/show/688906.Daddy_Long_Legs">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2329228-amy?shelf=books-i-have-re-read-time-and-time">books-i-have-re-read-time-and-time</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2329228-amy?shelf=re-read-in-2018">re-read-in-2018</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2329228-amy?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2329228-amy?shelf=re-read-in-2019">re-read-in-2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2329228-amy?shelf=old-fashion">old-fashion</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2329228-amy?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer120222419" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1952227289709406150"><b>2019 Review</b><br/>It could never be written today. Not to commit the cardinal sin and reference the m-o-v-i-e but I was re-watching the Fred Astaire version of of <i>Daddy Long Legs</i>, which I hated the first time I saw, and I realized that even for 1955 this was a hard plot to swallow. That&apos;s why they tweaked it the way they did and address the elephant in the room: you&apos;ve got quite the age and power gap between the main couple. <br/>But by golly I still love this book. And the movie isn&apos;t too bad either if you</span>
  <span id="freeText1952227289709406150" style="display:none"><b>2019 Review</b><br />It could never be written today. Not to commit the cardinal sin and reference the m-o-v-i-e but I was re-watching the Fred Astaire version of of <i>Daddy Long Legs</i>, which I hated the first time I saw, and I realized that even for 1955 this was a hard plot to swallow. That's why they tweaked it the way they did and address the elephant in the room: you've got quite the age and power gap between the main couple. <br />But by golly I still love this book. And the movie isn't too bad either if you don't mind random, unrelated dance numbers. <br /><br /><b>2018 Review</b><br />First, take a moment and appreciate the fact that this book was written in <i>1912.</i> That's incredible. <br />Second, I am 99.5% sure Judy is an ENFP. Like, maybe 99.7%. I relate to her so much.<br />Third, her initial college experience reminds me a bit of my own. Except instead of reading <i>Mother Goose</i> and <i>Little Women</i> and <i>Vanity Fair</i> for the first time, I read <i>Harry Potter</i> and <i>Twilight</i>. <br />Anyway, so, so, so good. I love this book. It always puts me in a good mood. <br /><br /><br /><b>First review:</b><br />What a positively adorable book! its one of those books you could add all sorts of old fashion words to describe, it was <i>lovely</i>. Judy Abbot is a young orphan girl who is suddenly and mysteriously given a chance to go to college, on the two requirements that she never learn the identity and that she write to him monthly. And so a very funny, delightful, charming, and absolutely sweet novel is born! I loved it!! Its definitely one of my favorite books now!! Absolutely adorable!!</span>
  <a data-text-id="1952227289709406150" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


